---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import HelpCallout from "../../components/HelpCallout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="For youth & young adults"
  description="Why teens and young adults face higher gambling risk, the forms that reach them, and what helps — for young people and the adults who support them."
>
  <header class="page-header">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="page-header__eyebrow">
        <a href="/understand-gambling">← Understand gambling</a>
      </p>
      <h1>For youth &amp; young adults</h1>
      <p class="page-header__lead">
        Younger people face a higher risk of gambling harm. Brains are still
        developing into the mid-20s, phones make betting constant, and gambling is
        increasingly woven into sports and games.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container prose">
      <h2>Forms that reach young people</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Online and app-based sports betting (age limits vary by state, often 18 or 21)</li>
        <li>Paid "loot boxes," skins, and in-game purchases that work like gambling</li>
        <li>Social casino apps and online games that mimic slots</li>
        <li>Online poker and casino games</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Why the risk is higher</h2>
      <p>
        Starting to gamble young raises the chance of problems later. Add constant
        phone access, heavy advertising that makes betting look normal, and a brain
        that is still wired for risk-taking, and it is easy to see why young people
        need extra support.
      </p>

      <h2>For parents and youth-serving adults</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Talk early and openly — curiosity, not lecture.</li>
        <li>Set clear limits on spending and screen time, and revisit them.</li>
        <li>Notice the signs: secrecy about money or apps, mood tied to games, chasing losses.</li>
        <li>Model healthy habits with money and games yourself.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>For young people</h2>
      <p>
        If gambling — or a game that feels like gambling — is taking more money,
        time, or headspace than you want, that is worth talking about. Asking for
        help is a strength, not a failure, and it is free. Talk to an adult you
        trust, or reach the helpline yourself.
      </p>

      <HelpCallout />

      <div class="sources">
        <h2>Learn more</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="https://www.ncpgambling.org/">National Council on Problem Gambling</a></li>
          <li><a href="https://www.samhsa.gov/mental-health/988">988 Suicide &amp; Crisis Lifeline (SAMHSA)</a></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
